[assistant] I investigated the remaining call sites for:
[assistant] 
[assistant] `org.mockito.internal.creation.proxy.MethodHandleProxy$LegacyVersion`
[assistant] 
[assistant] and there is no compliant public Mockito API path that reaches them on the configured GraalVM/JDK 25 runtime.
[assistant] 
[assistant] Why:
[assistant] 
[assistant] - `ProxyRealMethod.make()` tries `InvokeDefaultProxy` first on Java 16+.
[assistant] - On JDK 25, `InvocationHandler.invokeDefault(...)` exists, so Mockito selects `InvokeDefaultProxy`.
[assistant] - `MethodHandleProxy$LegacyVersion` is explicitly guarded for pre-module Java runtimes:
[assistant] 
[assistant] ```java
[assistant] Class.forName("java.lang.Module");
[assistant] throw new RuntimeException("Must not be used when modules are available");
[assistant] ```
[assistant] 
[assistant] - Therefore, on Java 9+ / GraalVM 25, `LegacyVersion` construction is intentionally rejected before its `resolve(...)` method can run.
[assistant] - The remaining uncovered call sites are inside `LegacyVersion.resolve(...)`, which is only reachable on Java 8-like runtimes where `java.lang.Module` is absent.
[assistant] 
[assistant] I left the active-class-dedicated test in place:
[assistant] 
[assistant] `tests/src/org.mockito/mockito-core/5.0.0/src/test/java/org_mockito/mockito_core/MethodHandleProxyInnerLegacyVersionTest.java`
[assistant] 
[assistant] It exercises the closest supported public API path: interface default-method invocation through Mockito’s proxy mock maker. I also fixed the access issue by making the nested interface public.
[assistant] 
[assistant] I did not force coverage through direct reflection, internal construction, fake/shadow classes, or classloader/JDK manipulation because those would violate the task rules and Native Image execution contract. No metadata files were edited.
